6812  return -1;
6813  if (str_it_width < 0 || content_width < (size_t)str_it_width)
6814  return -1;
6815 
6816  size_t padding = content_width - (size_t)str_it_width;
6817 
6818  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(print_n_strings(cntx, left, FT_SPACE));
6819  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(print_n_strings(cntx, 1, content_style_tag));
6820  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(buffer_print_range(cntx, beg, end));
6821  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(print_n_strings(cntx, 1, reset_content_style_tag));
6822  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(print_n_strings(cntx, padding, FT_SPACE));
6823  CHCK_RSLT_ADD_TO_WRITTEN(print_n_strings(cntx, right, FT_SPACE));
6824  return (int)written;
6825 
6826 clear:
6827  return -1;
6828 }

◆ ft_erase_range()

int ft_erase_range ( ft_table_t *  table,
size_t  top_left_row,
size_t  top_left_col,
size_t  bottom_right_row,
size_t  bottom_right_col 
)

Erase range of cells.

Range of cells is determined by 2 points (top-left and bottom-right) (both ends are included).

Paramètres
tablePointer to formatted table.
top_left_rowRow number of the top left cell in the range.
top_left_colColumn number of the top left cell in the range.
bottom_right_rowRow number of the bottom right cell in the range.
bottom_right_colColumn number of the bottom right cell in the range.
Renvoie
  • 0 - Operation was successfully implemented
  • (<0): In case of error

< Current row

< Current row

< Current column

< Current column

Définition à la ligne 2832 du fichier fort.c.

2835 {
2836  assert(table && table->rows);
2837  int status = FT_SUCCESS;
2838 
2839  size_t rows_n = vector_size(table->rows);
2840 
2841  if (top_left_row == FT_CUR_ROW)
2842  top_left_row = table->cur_row;
2843  if (bottom_right_row == FT_CUR_ROW)
2844  bottom_right_row = table->cur_row;
2845 
2846  if (top_left_col == FT_CUR_COLUMN)
2847  top_left_col = table->cur_row;
2848  if (bottom_right_col == FT_CUR_COLUMN)
2849  bottom_right_col = table->cur_row;
2850

2864  f_separator_t *separator = NULL;
2865 
2866  size_t n_iterations = MIN(rows_n - 1, bottom_right_row) - top_left_row + 1;
2867  size_t j = 0;
2868  i = top_left_row;
2869  for (j = 0; j < n_iterations; ++j) {
2870  row = VECTOR_AT(table->rows, i, f_row_t *);
2871  if (columns_in_row(row)) {
2872  ++i;
2873  } else {
2874  destroy_row(row);
2875  status = vector_erase(table->rows, i);
2876  if (FT_IS_ERROR(status))
2877  return status;
2878  if (i < vector_size(table->separators)) {
2879  separator = VECTOR_AT(table->separators, i, f_separator_t *);
2880  destroy_separator(separator);
2881  vector_erase(table->separators, i);
2882  }
2883  }
2884  }
2885 
2886  return FT_SUCCESS;
2887 }

Paramètres
tablePointer to formatted table.
Renvoie
  • 0: Success; data were written
  • (<0): In case of error.

Write specified number of strings to the table.

Write specified number of strings to the same number of consecutive cells in the current row.

Note
In most cases it is more preferable to use MACRO ft_write instead of ft_nwrite, which is more safe (ft_write automatically counts the number of string arguments and at compile check that all passed arguments are strings).

...Other strings to write.

  • (<0): In case of error

◆ ft_set_u8strwid_func()

void ft_set_u8strwid_func ( int(*)(const void *beg, const void *end, size_t *width)  u8strwid)

Set custom function to compute visible width of UTF-8 string.

libfort internally has a very simple logic to compute visible width of UTF-8 strings. It considers that each codepoint will occupy one position on the terminal in case of monowidth font (some east asians wide and fullwidth characters (see http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr11/tr11-33.html) will occupy 2 positions). This logic is very simple and covers wide range of cases. But obviously there a lot of cases when it is not sufficient. In such cases user should use some external libraries and provide an appropriate function to libfort.

Paramètres
u8strwidUser provided function to evaluate width of UTF-8 string ( beg - start of UTF-8 string, end - end of UTF-8 string (not included), width - pointer to the result). If function succeed it should return 0, otherwise some non- zero value. If function returns nonzero value libfort fallbacks to default internal algorithm.

Définition à la ligne 3743 du fichier fort.c.

3744 {
3745  buffer_set_u8strwid_func(u8strwid);
3746 }

Références buffer_set_u8strwid_func().

Voici le graphe d'appel pour cette fonction :

◆ ft_to_string()

const char* ft_to_string ( const ft_table_t *  table)

Convert table to string representation.

ft_table_t has ownership of the returned pointer. So there is no need to free it. To take ownership user should explicitly copy the returned string with strdup or similar functions.

Returned pointer may be later invalidated by:

  • Calling ft_destroy_table;
  • Other invocations of ft_to_string.
Paramètres
tableFormatted table.
Renvoie
  • The pointer to the string representation of formatted table, on success.
  • NULL on error.

Définition à la ligne 3405 du fichier fort.c.

3406 {
3407  return (const char *)ft_to_string_impl(table, CHAR_BUF);
3408 }

3322  if (FT_IS_ERROR(status)) {
3323  return NULL;
3324  }
3325  size_t n_codepoints = cod_height * cod_width + 1;
3326 
3327  /* Allocate string buffer for string representation */

3329  ((ft_table_t *)table)->conv_buffer = create_string_buffer(n_codepoints, b_type);
3330  if (table->conv_buffer == NULL)
3331  return NULL;
3332  }
3333  while (string_buffer_cod_width_capacity(table->conv_buffer) < n_codepoints) {

3337  }

3348  return NULL;
3349

3355

3369  cntx.b_type = b_type;
3370

3372  for (i = 0; i < context.table_properties->entire_table_properties.top_margin; ++i) {
3373  FT_CHECK(print_n_strings(&cntx, cod_width - 1/* minus new_line*/, FT_SPACE));
3374  FT_CHECK(print_n_strings(&cntx, 1, FT_NEWLINE));
3375  }
3376

3378  cur_sep = (i < sep_size) ? VECTOR_AT(table->separators, i, f_separator_t *) : NULL;
3379  cur_row = VECTOR_AT(table->rows, i, f_row_t *);
3380  enum f_hor_separator_pos separatorPos = (i == 0) ? TOP_SEPARATOR : INSIDE_SEPARATOR;
3381  context.row = i;
3382  FT_CHECK(print_row_separator(&cntx, col_vis_width_arr, cols, prev_row, cur_row, separatorPos, cur_sep));
3383  FT_CHECK(snprintf_row(cur_row, &cntx, col_vis_width_arr, cols, row_vis_height_arr[i]));
3384  prev_row = cur_row;
3385  }
3386  cur_row = NULL;
3387  cur_sep = (i < sep_size) ? VECTOR_AT(table->separators, i, f_separator_t *) : NULL;
3388  context.row = i;
3389  FT_CHECK(print_row_separator(&cntx, col_vis_width_arr, cols, prev_row, cur_row, BOTTOM_SEPARATOR, cur_sep));
3390 
3391  /* Print bottom margin */

3393  FT_CHECK(print_n_strings(&cntx, cod_width - 1/* minus new_line*/, FT_SPACE));
3394  FT_CHECK(print_n_strings(&cntx, 1, FT_NEWLINE));
3395  }
3396 
3397  result = buffer;
3398 
3399 clear:
3400  F_FREE(col_vis_width_arr);
3401  F_FREE(row_vis_height_arr);
3402  return result;
3403 }

7680  { 0x1D173, 0x1D182 }, { 0x1D185, 0x1D18B }, { 0x1D1AA, 0x1D1AD },
7681  { 0x1D242, 0x1D244 }, { 0xE0001, 0xE0001 }, { 0xE0020, 0xE007F },
7682  { 0xE0100, 0xE01EF }
7683  };
7684 
7685  /* We convert wchar_t to int32_t to avoid compiler warnings
7686  * about implicit integer conversions
7687  * https://github.com/seleznevae/libfort/issues/20
7688  *
7689  * note: didn't test if we can do it
7690  */
7691  int32_t ucs = (int32_t)wcs;
7692 
7693  /* test for 8-bit control characters */
7694  if (ucs == 0)
7695  return 0;
7696  if (ucs < 32 || (ucs >= 0x7f && ucs < 0xa0))
7697  return -1;
7698 
7699  /* binary search in table of non-spacing characters */
7700  if (bisearch(ucs, combining,
7701  sizeof(combining) / sizeof(struct interval) - 1))
7702  return 0;
7703 
7704  /* if we arrive here, ucs is not a combining or C0/C1 control character */
7705 
7706  return 1 +
7707  (ucs >= 0x1100 &&
7708  (ucs <= 0x115f || /* Hangul Jamo init. consonants */
7709  ucs == 0x2329 || ucs == 0x232a ||
7710  (ucs >= 0x2e80 && ucs <= 0xa4cf &&
7711  ucs != 0x303f) || /* CJK ... Yi */
7712  (ucs >= 0xac00 && ucs <= 0xd7a3) || /* Hangul Syllables */
7713  (ucs >= 0xf900 && ucs <= 0xfaff) || /* CJK Compatibility Ideographs */
7714  (ucs >= 0xfe10 && ucs <= 0xfe19) || /* Vertical forms */
7715  (ucs >= 0xfe30 && ucs <= 0xfe6f) || /* CJK Compatibility Forms */
7716  (ucs >= 0xff00 && ucs <= 0xff60) || /* Fullwidth Forms */
7717  (ucs >= 0xffe0 && ucs <= 0xffe6) ||
7718  (ucs >= 0x20000 && ucs <= 0x2fffd) ||
7719  (ucs >= 0x30000 && ucs <= 0x3fffd)));
7720 }

1332  // byte then return haystack
1333  if ('\0' == *((const char *)needle)) {
1334  return (void *)haystack;

1372  }

Références s().

Voici le graphe d'appel pour cette fonction :

◆ utf8cspn()

size_t utf8cspn ( const void *  src,
const void *  reject 
)
inline

Définition à la ligne 743 du fichier fort.c.

744 {
745  const char *s = (const char *)src;
746  size_t chars = 0;
747 
748  while ('\0' != *s) {
749  const char *r = (const char *)reject;
750  size_t offset = 0;
751 
752  while ('\0' != *r) {
753  // checking that if *r is the start of a utf8 codepoint
754  // (it is not 0b10xxxxxx) and we have successfully matched
755  // a previous character (0 < offset) - we found a match
756  if ((0x80 != (0xc0 & *r)) && (0 < offset)) {
757  return chars;
758  } else {
759  if (*r == s[offset]) {
760  // part of a utf8 codepoint matched, so move our checking
761  // onwards to the next byte
762  offset++;
763  r++;
764  } else {
765  // r could be in the middle of an unmatching utf8 code point,
766  // so we need to march it on to the next character beginning,
767 
768  do {
769  r++;
770  } while (0x80 == (0xc0 & *r));
771 
772  // reset offset too as we found a mismatch
773  offset = 0;
774  }
775  }
776  }
777 
778  // the current utf8 codepoint in src did not match reject, but src
779  // could have been partway through a utf8 codepoint, so we need to
780  // march it onto the next utf8 codepoint starting byte
781  do {
782  s++;
783  } while ((0x80 == (0xc0 & *s)));
784  chars++;
785  }
786 
787  return chars;
788 }

Définition à la ligne 792 du fichier fort.c.

793 {
794  const char *s = (const char *)src;
795  char *n = utf8_null;
796 
797  // figure out how many bytes (including the terminator) we need to copy first
798  size_t bytes = utf8size(src);
799 
800  n = (char *)malloc(bytes);
801 
802  if (utf8_null == n) {
803  // out of memory so we bail
804  return utf8_null;
805  } else {
806  bytes = 0;
807 
808  // copy src byte-by-byte into our new utf8 string
809  while ('\0' != s[bytes]) {
810  n[bytes] = s[bytes];
811  bytes++;
812  }
813 
814  // append null terminating byte
815  n[bytes] = '\0';
816  return n;
817  }

◆ utf8ncasecmp()

int utf8ncasecmp ( const void *  src1,
const void *  src2,
size_t  n 
)
inline

Définition à la ligne 927 du fichier fort.c.

928 {
929  utf8_int32_t src1_cp, src2_cp, src1_orig_cp, src2_orig_cp;
930 
931  do {
932  const unsigned char *const s1 = (const unsigned char *)src1;
933  const unsigned char *const s2 = (const unsigned char *)src2;
934 
935  // first check that we have enough bytes left in n to contain an entire
936  // codepoint
937  if (0 == n) {
938  return 0;
939  }
940 
941  if ((1 == n) && ((0xc0 == (0xe0 & *s1)) || (0xc0 == (0xe0 & *s2)))) {
942  const utf8_int32_t c1 = (0xe0 & *s1);
943  const utf8_int32_t c2 = (0xe0 & *s2);
944 
945  if (c1 < c2) {
946  return -1;
947  } else if (c1 > c2) {
948  return 1;
949  } else {
950  return 0;
951  }
952  }
953 
954  if ((2 >= n) && ((0xe0 == (0xf0 & *s1)) || (0xe0 == (0xf0 & *s2)))) {
955  const utf8_int32_t c1 = (0xf0 & *s1);
956  const utf8_int32_t c2 = (0xf0 & *s2);
957 
958  if (c1 < c2) {
959  return -1;
960  } else if (c1 > c2) {
961  return 1;
962  } else {
963  return 0;
964  }
965  }
966 
967  if ((3 >= n) && ((0xf0 == (0xf8 & *s1)) || (0xf0 == (0xf8 & *s2)))) {
968  const utf8_int32_t c1 = (0xf8 & *s1);
969  const utf8_int32_t c2 = (0xf8 & *s2);
970 
971  if (c1 < c2) {
972  return -1;
973  } else if (c1 > c2) {
974  return 1;
975  } else {
976  return 0;
977  }
978  }
979 
980  src1 = utf8codepoint(src1, &src1_cp);
981  src2 = utf8codepoint(src2, &src2_cp);
982  n -= utf8codepointsize(src1_cp);
983 
984  // Take a copy of src1 & src2
985  src1_orig_cp = src1_cp;
986  src2_orig_cp = src2_cp;
987 
988  // Lower srcs if required
989  src1_cp = utf8lwrcodepoint(src1_cp);
990  src2_cp = utf8lwrcodepoint(src2_cp);
991 
992  // Check if the lowered codepoints match
993  if ((0 == src1_orig_cp) && (0 == src2_orig_cp)) {
994  return 0;
995  } else if (src1_cp == src2_cp) {
996  continue;
997  }
998 
999  // If they don't match, then we return which of the original's are less
1000  if (src1_orig_cp < src2_orig_cp) {
1001  return -1;
1002  } else if (src1_orig_cp > src2_orig_cp) {
1003  return 1;
1004  }
1005  } while (0 < n);
1006 
1007  // both utf8 strings matched
1008  return 0;
1009 }

1088 
1089  // In case bytes is actually less than n, we need to set it
1090  // to be used later in the copy byte by byte.
1091  n = bytes;
1092 
1093  c = (char *)malloc(bytes + 1);
1094  if (utf8_null == c) {
1095  // out of memory so we bail
1096  return utf8_null;
1097  }
1098 
1099  bytes = 0;
1100 
1101  // copy src byte-by-byte into our new utf8 string
1102  while ('\0' != s[bytes] && bytes < n) {
1103  c[bytes] = s[bytes];
1104  bytes++;
1105  }
1106 
1107  // append null terminating byte
1108  c[bytes] = '\0';
1109  return c;
1110 }

Définition à la ligne 1112 du fichier fort.c.

1113 {
1114  const char *s = (const char *)src;
1115  const char *match = utf8_null;
1116  char c[5] = {'\0', '\0', '\0', '\0', '\0'};
1117 
1118  if (0 == chr) {
1119  // being asked to return position of null terminating byte, so
1120  // just run s to the end, and return!
1121  while ('\0' != *s) {
1122  s++;
1123  }
1124  return (void *)s;
1125  } else if (0 == ((int)0xffffff80 & chr)) {
1126  // 1-byte/7-bit ascii
1127  // (0b0xxxxxxx)
1128  c[0] = (char)chr;
1129  } else if (0 == ((int)0xfffff800 & chr)) {
1130  // 2-byte/11-bit utf8 code point
1131  // (0b110xxxxx 0b10xxxxxx)
1132  c[0] = 0xc0 | (char)(chr >> 6);
1133  c[1] = 0x80 | (char)(chr & 0x3f);
1134  } else if (0 == ((int)0xffff0000 & chr)) {
1135  // 3-byte/16-bit utf8 code point
1136  // (0b1110xxxx 0b10xxxxxx 0b10xxxxxx)
1137  c[0] = 0xe0 | (char)(chr >> 12);
1138  c[1] = 0x80 | (char)((chr >> 6) & 0x3f);
1139  c[2] = 0x80 | (char)(chr & 0x3f);
1140  } else { // if (0 == ((int)0xffe00000 & chr)) {
1141  // 4-byte/21-bit utf8 code point
1142  // (0b11110xxx 0b10xxxxxx 0b10xxxxxx 0b10xxxxxx)
1143  c[0] = 0xf0 | (char)(chr >> 18);
1144  c[1] = 0x80 | (char)((chr >> 12) & 0x3f);
1145  c[2] = 0x80 | (char)((chr >> 6) & 0x3f);
1146  c[3] = 0x80 | (char)(chr & 0x3f);
1147  }
1148 
1149  // we've created a 2 utf8 codepoint string in c that is
1150  // the utf8 character asked for by chr, and a null
1151  // terminating byte
1152 
1153  while ('\0' != *s) {
1154  size_t offset = 0;
1155 
1156  while (s[offset] == c[offset]) {
1157  offset++;
1158  }
1159 
1160  if ('\0' == c[offset]) {
1161  // we found a matching utf8 code point
1162  match = s;
1163  s += offset;
1164  } else {
1165  s += offset;
1166 
1167  // need to march s along to next utf8 codepoint start
1168  // (the next byte that doesn't match 0b10xxxxxx)
1169  if ('\0' != *s) {
1170  do {
1171  s++;
1172  } while (0x80 == (0xc0 & *s));
1173  }
1174  }
1175  }
1176 
1177  // return the last match we found (or 0 if no match was found)
1178  return (void *)match;
1179 }

)

Définition à la ligne 7389 du fichier fort.c.
